{{Unreferenced|date=May 2007}}
The '''Khartoum League''' began in 1952 and was a famous historical regional championship in [[Sudan]]. The teams playing in it were those from the three cities of the capital [[Khartoum]]; Khartoum, [[Bahri]], and [[Omdurman]].

The most famous winners of the Khartoum league were the two traditionally strong teams from Sudan, [[Al-Merrikh]] and [[Al-Hilal (Omdurman)|Al-Hilal]]. They won the championship 17 and 16 times respectively before their eventual withdrawal in 1997. No team had exceeded the number of tiles of Al-Merreikh even though the club has not taken part in the competition since early 1997.

{{Football in Sudan}}
{{Sudan-sport-stub}}
{{Africa-footy-competition-stub}}

[[Category:Football leagues in Sudan]]

The Pakistan national Team, led by [[Asif Iqbal (cricketer, born 1943)|Asif Iqbal]], came to Bangladesh for a short tour in January, 1980, in the middle of their long tour of India. Two matches were scheduled, a two-day match at [[Chittagong]]. followed by a 3-Day fixture at [[Dacca]]. Unortunately, trouble broke out during the Tea break in the second day of the match at Chittagong, and the remainder of the tour was abandoned.
==Scores in brief==
{| class="wikitable" |- bgcolor="#efefef" ! Date ! Match ! Venue ! ! ! Result |- || Jan 2-3 || 2-Day Match||[[Chittagong]]|| [[Pakistani cricket team|Pakistan]]: 179/5 (Decl.) ([[Mudassar Nazar]] 77, [[Sadiq Mohammad]] 35, [[Majid Khan (cricketer, born 1946)|Majid Khan]] 21, [[Yousuf Rahman]] 2/38) & 138/3 (Decl)( Talat Mirza 43, [[Mohsin Khan (Pakistani cricketer)|Mohsin Khan]] 34)|| BCCB 114 (Yousuf Rahman 28, [[Raqibul Hasan (cricketer, born 1953)|Raqibul Hasan]] 16, [[Rafiqul Alam (cricketer)|Rafiqul Alam]] 16, [[Shafiq-ul-Haq]] 16, [[Abdul Kadir (Bangladeshi cricketer)|Abdul Kadir]] 5/49, [[Majid Khan (cricketer, born 1946)|Majid Khan]] 2/4, [[Iqbal Qasim]] 2/24) & 65/3 (Yousuf Rahman 17, [[Iqbal Qasim]] 2/22) || Match Abandoned |- || Jan 5-7 || 3-Day Match || [[Dhaka]]|| - || - || Match Abandoned |- |}
==Unfortunate incident== A section of the crowd entered the ground immediately after the tea break on the second day attacking the Pak players. They were angry over the alleged remarks by some Pak cricketers about the independence of Bangladesh. It is still impossible to verify the truth of the allegation. But the match was instantly called off, and consequently the 3-Day match at [[Dhaka]] was cancelled. This was a big disappointment for the Dhaka crowd, as more than 30,000 tickets were already sold.
==Uneasy relations== As the tourists left to restart their tour of India, the cricketing relationship between Bangladesh and Pakistan reached a new low. A tour of Pakistan by the Bangladesh team, scheduled for the following month was promptly cancelled. Though, [[Mushtaq Mohammad]] led a PIA side in Feb. 1984, it was really the tour of the Omar Quareshi XI, (led by [[Imran Khan]]), in Jan 1986, that eventually normalized the relationship. A Bangladeshi team, led by [[Gazi Ashraf]] toured [[Bangladeshi cricket team in Pakistan in 1986|Pakistan]] in March, and the two teams met on their first official ODI on 31 March, in the 2nd Asia Cup. <ref>Hasan Babli. "Antorjartik Crickete Bangladesh". ''Khelar Bhuban Prakashani'', November, 1994.</ref>
